  "topic": "Portuguese Present Tense (Presente do Indicativo)",
  "language_pair": "en-pt",
  "target_language": "pt",
  "native_language": "en",
  "description": "Portuguese Present Tense (Presente do Indicativo) – for English speakers. Used for habits, general truths, repeated actions, current states, feelings, near future (with time expressions), and sometimes ongoing actions (especially in Brazil). Very similar to English Present Simple, but with important differences in verb endings and some verbs that use the present for 'I am doing' meanings.",
  "grammar_focus": {
    "rule": "Verb stem + present tense endings (regular verbs change according to conjugation group: -ar, -er, -ir)",
    "suffixes": {
      "eu (I)": "-o",
      "tu (you informal)": "-as / -es / -is",
      "você/ele/ela (you formal/he/she/it)": "-a / -e / -e",
      "nós (we)": "-amos / -emos / -imos",
      "vocês/eles/elas (you plural/they)": "-am / -em / -em"
    },
    "note_en": "Most regular verbs follow one of three patterns: -AR (falar), -ER (comer), -IR (partir). Irregular verbs are very common (ser, estar, ter, ir, fazer, dizer, etc.). In Brazilian Portuguese the present is often used for both 'I do' and 'I am doing' (Eu falo português = I speak Portuguese / I am speaking Portuguese right now). In European Portuguese 'estar + gerúndio' is more common for ongoing actions. Negation: não + verb. Questions: just intonation or inversion (Você fala inglês?)."
  },
